Experts said training was ‘heavily geared’ towards young people leaving older workers vulnerable when companies start ‘shedding’ jobs . 
  Association of Accounting Technicians said over-55s had same literacy and numeracy skills as those aged 16 to 24 – and were worse at these skills than colleagues in their 30s and 40s . 
  Majority of older workers did not believe better computer skills would help them in current job . 
 